A026001.name: a(n) = T(3n,n), where T = Delannoy triangle (A008288).
formula: G.f.: F(G^(-1)(x)) where F = (2-t)/(3*t^2-8*t+2) and G = t*(t-1)^3/(t-2). - _Mark van Hoeij_, Oct 30 2011

A026002.name: a(n) = T(n,n+2), where T = Delannoy triangle (A008288).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..floor(n/2)} k*A110220(n, k). - _Emeric Deutsch_, Jul 16 2005
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} C(n, k)*C(n+2, k)*2^k. - _Paul Barry_, Jan 23 2006
a(n+1) = 1/2^(n+1) * Sum_{k >= 2} 1/2^k * binomial(n + k, n)*binomial(n + k, n + 2).

A026003.name: a(n) = T([n/2],[(n+1)/2]), where T = Delannoy triangle (A008288).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..floor(n/2)} C(n-k, k)*C(n-2k, floor((n-2k)/2)). - _Paul Barry_, Jul 30 2005

A026004.name: a(n) = T(3n+1,n), where T = Catalan triangle (A008315).
formula: G.f.: ((sqrt(x)*sin(2/3*arcsin((3*sqrt(3)*sqrt(x))/2)))/sqrt(4/3-9*x)-cos(1/3*arccos(1-(27*x)/2))+1)/(3*x). - conjectured by _Harvey P. Dale_, Jun 30 2011

A026005.name: a(n) = T(4*n,n), where T = Catalan triangle (A008315).
formula: G.f.: (g-2)*g^2/(3*g-4) where g = 1+x*g^4 is the g.f. of A002293. - _Mark van Hoeij_, Nov 11 2011

A026007.name: Expansion of Product_{m>=1} (1 + q^m)^m; number of partitions of n into distinct parts, where n different parts of size n are available.
formula: G.f. Product_{m>=1} (1+x^m)^m. Weighout transform of natural numbers (A000027). Euler transform of A026741. - _Franklin T. Adams-Watters_, Mar 16 2006

A026008.name: a(n) = T(n, floor(n/2)), where T = Catalan triangle (A008315).

A026009.name: Triangular array T read by rows: T(n,0) = 1 for n >= 0; T(1,1) = 1; and for n >= 2, T(n,k) = T(n-1,k-1) + T(n-1,k) for k = 1,2,...,[(n+1)/2]; T(n,n/2 + 1) = T(n-1,n/2) if n is even.
formula: T(n, k) = binomial(n, k) - binomial(n, k-3). - Darko Marinov (marinov(AT)lcs.mit.edu), May 17 2001
Sum_{k=0..floor((n+2)/2)} T(n, k) = A026010(n). - _G. C. Greubel_, Mar 18 2021

A026010.name: a(n) = number of (s(0), s(1), ..., s(n)) such that s(i) is a nonnegative integer and |s(i) - s(i-1)| = 1 for i = 1,2,...,n and s(0) = 2. Also a(n) = sum of numbers in row n+1 of array T defined in A026009.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} binomial(floor((n+k)/2), floor(k/2)). - _Paul Barry_, Jul 15 2004
Inverse binomial transform of A005774: (1, 3, 9, 26, 75, 216, ...). - _Gary W. Adamson_, Oct 22 2007
a(n) = (1/2)^((5 - (-1)^n)/2)*(6*n + 7 - 3*(-1)^n)*Catalan((2*n + 1 - (-1)^n)/4), where Catalan is the Catalan number = A000108. - _G. C. Greubel_, Nov 08 2018

A026012.name: Second differences of Catalan numbers A000108.
formula: Expansion of (1+x^1*C^3)*C^1, where C = (1-(1-4*x)^(1/2))/(2*x) is g.f. for Catalan numbers, A000108.

A026013.name: a(n) = number of (s(0), s(1), ..., s(2n)) such that s(i) is a nonnegative integer and |s(i) - s(i-1)| = 1 for i = 1,2,...,n, s(0) = 2, s(2n) = 4. Also a(n) = T(2n,n-1), where T is the array defined in A026009.
formula: G.f.: (x + x^2*C^3)*C^3 where C = g.f. for Catalan numbers A000108.
a(n) = C(n+3) - 4*C(n+2) + 3*C(n+1) + Sum_{j=0..n-1} C(j+1)*C(n-j-1), where C(n) are the Catalan numbers (A000108).
a(n) = binomial(2*n, n-1) - binomial(2*n, n-4) = A026009(2*n, n-1). (End)

A026014.name: a(n) = number of (s(0), s(1), ..., s(2n)) such that s(i) is a nonnegative integer and |s(i) - s(i-1)| = 1 for i = 1,2,...,n, s(0) = 2, s(2n) = 6. Also a(n) = T(2n,n-2), where T is the array defined in A026009.
formula: G.f.: (1-x)*x^2*C(x)^7, where C(x) is the g.f. of the Catalan numbers (A000108).
a(n) = binomial(2*n, n-2) - binomial(2*n, n-5) = A026009(2*n, n-2).
a(n) = 1 if n = 2 else f(n) - f(n-1), where f(n) = Sum_{j=0..n-2} C(n-j-2)*(C(j+5) -4*C(j+4) +3*C(j+3)) and C(n) are the Catalan numbers. (End)
a(n) = 21*((n*(n-1)*(n^2+n+4)/((n+2)*(n+3)*(n+4)*(n+5)))*C(n), where C(n) are the Catalan numbers. (End)

A026015.name: a(n) = number of (s(0), s(1), ..., s(2n)) such that s(i) is a nonnegative integer and |s(i) - s(i-1)| = 1 for i = 1,2,...,n, s(0) = 2, s(2n) = 8. Also a(n) = T(2n,n-3), where T is the array defined in A026009.
formula: G.f.: (1-x)*x^3*C(x)^9, where C(x) is the g.f. of the Catalan numbers (A000108).
a(n) = binomial(2*n, n-3) - binomial(2*n, n-6) = A026009(2*n, n-3).
a(n) = f(n) - f(n-1), where f(n) = Sum_{j=0..n-3} C(n-j-3)*(C(j+7) -6*C(j+6) +10*C(j+5) -4*C(j+4)) and C(n) are the Catalan numbers. (End)

A026016.name: a(n) = binomial(2*n-1, n) - binomial(2*n-1, n+3).
formula: Expansion of (1+x^1*C^3)*C^2, where C = (1-(1-4*x)^(1/2))/(2*x) is g.f. for Catalan numbers, A000108.
a(n) = C(n) + Sum_{j=0..n-2} C(n-j-2)*(C(j+3) - 2*C(j+2)), where C(n) are the Catalan numbers. (End)

A026017.name: a(n) = number of (s(0), s(1), ..., s(2n-1)) such that s(i) is a nonnegative integer and |s(i) - s(i-1)| = 1 for i = 1,2,...,n, s(0) = 2, s(2n-1) = 5. Also a(n) = T(2n-1,n-2), where T is the array defined in A026009.
formula: Expansion of (1+x^1*C^3)*C^4, where C = (1-(1-4*x)^(1/2))/(2*x) is g.f. for Catalan numbers, A000108.

A026018.name: a(n) = number of (s(0), s(1), ..., s(2n-1)) such that s(i) is a nonnegative integer and |s(i) - s(i-1)| = 1 for i = 1,2,...,n, s(0) = 2, s(2n-1) = 7. Also a(n) = T(2n-1,n-3), where T is the array defined in A026009.

A026020.name: a(n) = binomial(4n, n) - binomial(4n, n - 3).
formula: G.f.: (g - 2)*(1 - g + g^2)*g/(3*g - 4) where g = 1 + x*g^4 is the g.f. of A002293. - _Mark van Hoeij_, Nov 11 2011
a(n) = A005810(n) - A004333(n) for n > 2 - _Felix Fröhlich_, Jun 06 2019

A026021.name: T(n,[ n/2 ]), where T is the array defined in A026009.

A026022.name: Triangular array T read by rows: T(n,0) = 1 for n >= 0; T(n,k) = C(n,k) for k = 1,2,...,n, for n = 1,2,3; and for n >= 4, T(n,k) = T(n-1,k-1) + T(n-1,k) for k = 1,2,...,[ (n+2)/2 ] and T(n,(n+3)/2) = T(n-1,(n+1)/2) if n is odd.
formula: T(n, k) = C(n, k) - C(n, k-4). - _Ralf Stephan_, Jan 09 2005

A026023.name: a(n) = number of (s(0), s(1), ..., s(n)) such that s(i) is a nonnegative integer and |s(i) - s(i-1)| = 1 for i = 1,2,...,n and s(0) = 3. Also a(n) = Sum{T(n,k), k = 0,1,...,[ (n+3)/2 ]}, where T is defined in A026022.

A026026.name: a(n) = number of (s(0), s(1), ..., s(2n-1)) such that s(i) is a nonnegative integer and |s(i) - s(i-1)| = 1 for i = 1,2,...,n, s(0) = 3, s(2n-1) = 4. Also a(n) = T(2n-1,n-1), where T is defined in A026022.
formula: Expansion of (1+x^2*C^4)*C^3, where C = (1-(1-4*x)^(1/2))/(2*x) is g.f. for Catalan numbers, A000108.

A026027.name: a(n) = number of (s(0), s(1), ..., s(2n-1)) such that s(i) is a nonnegative integer and |s(i) - s(i-1)| = 1 for i = 1,2,...,n, s(0) = 3, s(2n-1) = 6. Also a(n) = T(2n-1,n-2), where T is defined in A026022.

A026029.name: Number of (s(0), s(1), ..., s(2n)) such that s(i) is a nonnegative integer and |s(i) - s(i-1)| = 1 for i = 1,2,....,n, s(0) = 3, s(2n) = 3. Also T(2n,n), where T is defined in A026022.
formula: Expansion of (1+x^2*C^4)*C^2, where C = (1-(1-4*x)^(1/2))/(2*x) is g.f. for Catalan numbers, A000108.
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} C(n, k)*Sum_{i=0..k} C(k, 2i)*A000108(i+1). - _Paul Barry_, Jul 18 2003

A026030.name: a(n) = T(2n,n-1), where T is defined in A026022.
formula: a(n) = C(2n, n-1) - C(2n, n-5). G.f.: (1+x^2C^4)*C^4, where C=(1-sqrt(1-4x))/(2x). - _Ralf Stephan_, Jan 09 2005

A026031.name: a(n) = number of (s(0), s(1), ..., s(2n)) such that s(i) is a nonnegative integer and |s(i) - s(i-1)| = 1 for i = 1,2,...,n, s(0) = 3, s(2n) = 7. Also a(n) = T(2n,n-2), where T is defined in A026022.
formula: C(2n, n-2) - C(2n, n-6). G.f.: (1+x^2C^4)*C^6, where C=(1-sqrt(1-4x))/(2x). - _Ralf Stephan_, Jan 09 2005

A026033.name: C(4n,n) - C(4n,n-4).

A026122.name: a(n) = number of (s(0),s(1),...,s(n)) such that every s(i) is a nonnegative integer, s(0) = 1, s(n) = 1, |s(1) - s(0)| = 1, |s(i) - s(i-1)| <= 1 for i >= 2. Also a(n) = T(n,n), where T is the array in A026120.
formula: G.f.: (-1+(1-z)^2M^2), with M the g.f. of the Motzkin numbers (A001006). [corrected by _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Sep 17 2019]

A026123.name: a(n) = number of (s(0),s(1),...,s(n)) such that every s(i) is a nonnegative integer, s(0) = 1, s(n) = 2, |s(1) - s(0)| = 1, |s(i) - s(i-1)| <= 1 for i >= 2. Also a(n) = T(n,n-1), where T is the array in A026120; a(n) = U(n,n+1), where U is the array in A026148.
formula: G.f.: z^2(-1+(1-z)^2M^3), with M the g.f. of the Motzkin numbers (A001006).

A026124.name: a(n) = number of (s(0),s(1),...,s(n)) such that every s(i) is a nonnegative integer, s(0) = 1, s(n) = 3, |s(1) - s(0)| = 1, |s(i) - s(i-1)| <= 1 for i >= 2. Also a(n) = T(n,n-2), where T is the array in A026120.
formula: G.f.: z^2(1-z)^2M^4, with M the g.f. of the Motzkin numbers (A001006).

A026125.name: a(n) = number of (s(0),s(1),...,s(n)) such that every s(i) is a nonnegative integer, s(0) = 1, s(n) = 4, |s(1) - s(0)| = 1, |s(i) - s(i-1)| <= 1 for i >= 2. Also a(n) = T(n,n-3), where T is the array in A026120.
formula: G.f.: z^3(1-z)^2M^5, with M the g.f. of the Motzkin numbers (A001006).

A026126.name: a(n) = number of (s(0),s(1),...,s(n)) such that every s(i) is a nonnegative integer, s(0) = 1, s(n) = 5, |s(1) - s(0)| = 1, |s(i) - s(i-1)| <= 1 for i >= 2. Also a(n) = T(n,n-4), where T is the array in A026120.

A026133.name: a(n) = T(n,[ n/2 ] - 1), where T is the array in A026120.

A026134.name: a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} T(k, k-1), where T is the array in A026120.
formula: G.f.: z(1-z)M^3, with M the g.f. of the Motzkin numbers (A001006).

A026135.name: Number of (s(0),s(1),...,s(n)) such that every s(i) is a nonnegative integer, s(0) = 1, |s(1) - s(0)| = 1, |s(i) - s(i-1)| <= 1 for i >= 2. Also sum of numbers in row n+1 of the array T defined in A026120.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} binomial(n-1, k-1)*binomial(k+1, floor((k+1)/2)). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Sep 18 2003
G.f. = (1+z)*(1+z^2)/(1-z) where z=x*A001006(x). [From _R. J. Mathar_, Jul 07 2009]

A026136.name: For n >= 2, let L=n-[ n/2 ], R=n+[ n/2 ]; then a(L)=n if a(L) not yet defined, else a(R)=n; thus |a(n)-n|=[ (1/2)*a(n) ].

A026137.name: a(n) = position of n in A026136.

A026138.name: a(n) = n-th number k such that s(j) < s(k) for all j < k, where s = A026136.

A026139.name: a(n) = s(k), where k is the n-th number such that s(j) < s(k) for all j < k, where s = A026136. Also a(n) = 2*t(n) - 1, where t = A026138.

A026142.name: For n >= 2, let h=[ (n+1)/2 ], L=n-h, R=n+h; a(L)=n if a(L) not yet defined, else a(R)=n; thus |a(n)-n| = [ (a(n)+1)/2 ].

A026143.name: a(n) = position of n in A026142.

A026144.name: a(n) = n-th number k such that s(j) < s(k) for all j < k, where s = A026142.

A026147.name: a(n) = position of n-th 1 in A001285 or A010059 (Thue-Morse sequence).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..2n} mod(-2 + Sum_{j=0..k} floor(C(k, j)/2)}, 3). - _Paul Barry_, Dec 24 2004
a(n) + A010059(n+1) = 2n + 2 for n >= 0. - _Clark Kimberling_, Oct 06 2014

A026148.name: Irregular triangular array T read by rows: T(n,0) = 1 for i >= 0, T(1,1) = 1,T(2,1) = 1, T(2,2) = 2, T(2,3) = 1, T(2,4) = 1 and for n >= 3, T(n,1) = n-1,  T(n,k) = T(n-1,k-2) + T(n-1,k-1) + T(n-1,k) for k=2,...,n+1, and T(n, k+2) = T(n-1, k) + T(n-1, k+1).

A026150.name: a(0) = a(1) = 1; a(n+2) = 2*a(n+1) + 2*a(n).
formula: a(n) = a(n-1) + A083337(n-1). A083337(n)/a(n) converges to sqrt(3). - Mario Catalani (mario.catalani(AT)unito.it), Apr 29 2003
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} A098158(n,k)*3^(n - k). - _Philippe Deléham_, Dec 26 2007
a(n) = upper left and lower right terms of [1, 1; 3, 1]^n. (1 + sqrt(3))^n = a(n) + A083337(n)/(sqrt(3)). - _Gary W. Adamson_, Mar 12 2008

If p[1] = 1, and p[i] = 3, (i > 1), and if A is Hessenberg matrix of order n defined by: A[i,j] = p[j-i+1], (i <= j), A[i,j] = -1, (i = j + 1), and A[i,j] = 0 otherwise. Then, for n >= 1, a(n) = det A. - _Milan Janjic_, Apr 29 2010
a(n) = 2 * A052945(n-1). - _Vladimir Joseph Stephan Orlovsky_, Mar 24 2011
a(n) = round((1 + sqrt(3))^n/2) for n > 0. - _Bruno Berselli_, Feb 04 2013
G.f.: G(0)/2, where G(k)= 1 + 1/(1 - x*(3*k - 1)/(x*(3*k + 2) - 1/G(k+1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, May 25 2013
a(n) = (-sqrt(2)*i)^n*T(n,sqrt(2)*i/2), with i = sqrt(-1) and the Chebyshev T-polynomials (A053120). - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Feb 10 2018

formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} binomial(n, k)*binomial(k+1, floor(k/2)). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Sep 18 2003

A026166.name: For n >= 2, let h=floor((n-1)/2), L=n-h, R=n+h; then a(L)=n if a(L) not yet defined, otherwise a(R)=n; thus |a(n)-n| = floor((1/2)*(a(n)-1)).
formula: This formula does not permit us to calculate the n-th term of the sequence, since the equation |x-n| = floor((1/2)*(x-1)) has at least 2 integer solutions for all n. - _Michel Dekking_, Nov 26 2019

A026168.name: a(n) = n-th number k such that s(j)<s(k) for all j<k. Also a(n) = (n-1)st number k such that s(k)>k, for n >= 3, where s = A026166.

A026169.name: a(n) = s(k), where k is the n-th number k such that s(j)<s(k) for all j<k, where s = A026166.

A026177.name: For n >= 2, let h=floor(n/2), L=n-h, R=n+h; then a(R)=n if n odd or a(L) already defined, otherwise a(L)=n.
formula: a(n) = ceiling(2n/3) if A060236(n)=1, otherwise a(n) = 2n, where A060236(n) is the lowest non-0 ternary digit of n.

A026178.name: a(n) is the position of n in A026177.
formula: a(n) = n/2 if n even and A060236(n)=1, otherwise a(n) = floor(3n/2), where A060236(n) is the lowest non-0 ternary digit of n.

A026179.name: a(n) = n-th number k such that s(j) < s(k) for all j < k, where s = A026177.
formula: Let the sequence 1, 0, 1, 1, 0, 0, 1, 0, 1, ... be defined as the fixed point of the morphism 1->101 and 0->100, starting from a(1)=1. The indices of 0 are 2, 5, 6, 8, 11, 14, 17, 18, ... (this sequence with first term omitted). - _Philippe Deléham_, Jun 27 2006
After first term, these are the numbers of the form (3i+2)*3^j, where i >= 0, j >= 0. - _Clark Kimberling_, Oct 19 2016

A026180.name: a(n) = s(k), where k is the n-th number such that s(j)<s(k) for all j<k, where s = A026177.

formula: a(n) = n/2 if n even and A060236(n)=2, otherwise a(n) = ceiling(3n/2), where A060236(n) is the lowest non-0 ternary digit of n.

A026215.name: a(n) = position of n in A026214.

A026218.name: a(n) = (1/3)*(s(n) + 2), where s(n) is the n-th number congruent to 1 mod 3 in A026177.

A026222.name: a(n) = n-th number k such that s(k)=t(k), where s = A026136, t = A026142.

A026224.name: Numbers n such that t(n) = s(n) + 1, where s = A026136, t = A026142.

A026226.name: a(n) = n-th number k such that s(k) = t(k), where s = A026136, t = A026166.

A026229.name: n-th number k such that t(k) = s(k) - 2, where s = A026142, t = A026166.

A026233.name: a(n) = j if n is the j-th prime, else a(n) = k if n is the k-th nonprime.

A026234.name: In the sequence of positive integers, swap the k-th prime and k-th nonprime, for k = 1,2,3,...
formula: If n is prime, then a(n) = A018252(n), else a(n) = A000040(n). - _M. F. Hasler_, Jan 29 2014

A026236.name: a(n) = (s(n) + 1)/2, where s(n) is the n-th odd number in A026234.

A026237.name: a(n) = position of n in A026236.

A026238.name: a(n) = j if n is the j-th prime, else a(n) = k if n is the k-th composite.

A026239.name: Beginning with the natural numbers, swap the k-th prime and k-th composite.
formula: a(1) = 1 and a(n) = if n is prime then A002808(A049084(n)) else A000040(A066246(n)) for n>1. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Dec 13 2001

A026242.name: a(n) = j if n is L(j), else a(n) = k if n is U(k), where L = A000201, U = A001950 (lower and upper Wythoff sequences).
formula: a(n) = a(m) if a(m) has already occurred exactly once and n = a(m) + m; otherwise, a(n) = least positive integer that has not yet occurred.
n = a(n) + a(n-1) unless n = A089910(m); if n = A089910(m), then n = a(n) + a(n-1) - m. - _Bob Selcoe_, Sep 20 2014

A026243.name: a(n) = A000522(n) - 2.
formula: a(n) = n*(a(n-1)+2)-1 for n>1, a(1) = 0. - _Alois P. Heinz_, May 25 2012
Conjecture: a(n) +(-n-2)*a(n-1) +(2*n-1)*a(n-2) +(-n+2)*a(n-3)=0. - _R. J. Mathar_, Jun 23 2013 [Confirmed by _Altug Alkan_, May 18 2018]

A026244.name: a(n) = 4^n*(4^n+1)/2.
formula: With interpolated zeros 0, 1, 0, 10, ... has a(n) = (4^n - (-4)^n + 2*2^n - 2*(-2)^n)/16 and counts walks of length n between adjacent vertices of the 4-cube.
a(n) = 8^n*T(n,5/4) where T is the Chebyshev polynomial of first kind;
a(n) = 64^n * a(-n) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Jul 02 2017

A026269.name: a(n) = number of (s(0), s(1), ..., s(n)) such that every s(i) is a nonnegative integer, s(0) = 0 = s(n), s(1) = 1, |s(i) - s(i-1)| <= 1 for i >= 2, |s(2) - s(1)| = 1, |s(3) - s(2)| = 1 if s(2) = 1. Also a(n) = T(n,n) and a(n) = Sum{T(k,k-1)}, k = 1,2,...,n, where T is array in A026268.

A026270.name: Number of (s(0), s(1), ..., s(n)) such that every s(i) is a nonnegative integer, s(0) = 0, s(1) = 1 = s(n), |s(i) - s(i-1)| <= 1 for i >= 2, |s(2) - s(1)| = 1, |s(3) - s(2)| = 1 if s(2) = 1. Also T(n,n-1), where T is the array in A026268.

formula: a(n) = floor(r*r*(n+2r-3)), where r = (1+sqrt(5))/2 = A001622. [Corrected by _Tom Edgar_, Jan 30 2015]
a(n) = 3*n - floor[(n+1)/(1+phi)], phi = (1+sqrt(5))/2. - Joshua Tobin (tobinrj(AT)tcd.ie), May 31 2008
a(n) = A003622(n+1) - 1 for n>1 (conjectured). - _Michel Marcus_, Oct 30 2020
This conjectured formula follows directly from the formula a(n) = floor((n+1)*r^2)-2 in my March 12, 2018 comment above. - _Michel Dekking_, Oct 31 2020

a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} binomial(2*n-k, k)*binomial(k, n-k). - _Paul Barry_, Jul 25 2005
a(n) = (3*binomial(2*n-1,n-1) - d(n-1))/2, where d(n) = Sum_{k=floor(n/2)..n} binomial(2*n-k, k)*binomial(k, n-k).

a(n+3) + a(n+2) = 3 + a(n+1) + a(n). a(n+3) * a(n) = - 1 + a(n+2) * a(n+1). a(n) = -a(-n) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Jun 15 2005

a(n) = A001318(n) - A001318(n-1) for n > 0. - _Jonathan Sondow_, Jan 28 2013
a(n) = numerator(1 - 2/(n+2)), n >= 0; a(n) = denominator(1 - 2/n), n >= 1. - _Kival Ngaokrajang_, Jul 17 2014
a(n) = Sum_{i = floor(n/2)..floor((n+1)/2)} i. - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Apr 27 2016
Euler transform of length 3 sequence [1, 2, -1]. - _Michael Somos_, Jan 20 2017

A026768.name: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..floor(n/2)} T(n-k,k), T given by A026758.

A026769.name: Triangular array T read by rows: T(n,0)=T(n,n)=1 for n >= 0; T(2,1)=2; for n >= 3 and 1<=k<=n-1, T(n,k) = T(n-1,k-1) + T(n-2,k-1) + T(n-1,k) if 1<=k<=(n-1)/2, else T(n,k) = T(n-1,k-1) + T(n-1,k).
formula: For n>=2*k, T(n,k) = coefficient of x^k in G(x)*S(x)^(n-2*k). For n<=2*k, T(n,k) = coefficient of x^(n-k) in G(x)*C(x)^(2*k-n). Here C(x)=(1-sqrt(1-4x))/(2*x) is o.g.f. for A000108, S(x)=(1-x - sqrt(1-6*x+x^2) )/(2*x) is o.g.f. for A006318, and G(x)=1/(1-x*(C(x)+S(x))) is o.g.f. for A026770. - _Max Alekseyev_, Dec 02 2015

A026770.name: a(n) = T(2n,n), T given by A026769.
formula: O.g.f.: 1/(1-x*(C(x)+S(x))), where C(x)=(1-sqrt(1-4x))/(2*x) is o.g.f. for A000108 and S(x)=(1-x-sqrt(1-6*x+x^2))/(2*x) is o.g.f. for A006318. - _Max Alekseyev_, Dec 02 2015

A026771.name: a(n) = T(2n,n-1), T given by A026769.

A026772.name: a(n) = T(2n, n-2), T given by A026769.

A026775.name: a(n) = T(n, floor(n/2)), T given by A026769.

A026779.name: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..floor(n/2)} T(n-k,k), T given by A026769.

A026780.name: Triangular array T read by rows: T(n,0)=T(n,n)=1 for n >= 0; for n >= 2 and 1 <= k <= n-1, T(n,k) = T(n-1,k-1) + T(n-2,k-1) + T(n-1,k) if 1 <= k <= floor(n/2), else T(n,k) = T(n-1,k-1) + T(n-1,k).
formula: For n>=2*k, T(n,k) = coefficient of x^k in F(x)*S(x)^(n-2*k). For n<=2*k, T(n,k) = coefficient of x^(n-k) in F(x)*C(x)^(2*k-n). Here C(x) = (1 - sqrt(1-4x))/(2*x) is o.g.f. for A000108, S(x) = (1 - x - sqrt(1-6*x+x^2))/(2*x) is o.g.f. for A006318, and F(x) = S(x)/(1 - x*C(x)*S(x)) is o.g.f. for A026781. - _Max Alekseyev_, Jan 13 2015

A026781.name: a(n) = T(2n,n), T given by A026780.
formula: O.g.f.: S(x)/(1-x*C(x)*S(x)) = (S(x)-C(x))/(x*C(x)), where C(x)=(1-sqrt(1-4x))/(2*x) is o.g.f. for A000108 and S(x)=(1-x-sqrt(1-6*x+x^2))/(2*x) is o.g.f. for A006318. - _Max Alekseyev_, Jan 13 2015

A026782.name: a(n) = T(2n,n-1), T given by A026780.

A026783.name: a(n) = T(2n, n-2), T given by A026780.

A026784.name: a(n) = T(2n-1, n-1), T given by A026780.

A026785.name: a(n) = T(2n-1, n-2), T given by A026780.

A026786.name: a(n) = T(n, floor(n/2)), T given by A026780.

A026787.name: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} T(n,k), T given by A026780.
formula: O.g.f.: F(x^2)*(1/(1-x*S(x^2))+C(x^2)*x/(1-x*C(x^2))), where C(x)=(1-sqrt(1-4x))/(2*x) is o.g.f. for A000108, S(x)=(1-x-sqrt(1-6*x+x^2))/(2*x) is o.g.f. for A006318, and F(x)=S(x)/(1-x*C(x)*S(x)) is o.g.f. for A026781. - _Max Alekseyev_, Jan 13 2015

A026788.name: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..floor(n/2)} T(n,k), T given by A026780.

A026789.name: a(n) = Sum_{i=0..n} Sum_{j=0..n} T(i,j), T given by A026780.

A026790.name: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..floor(n/2)} T(n-k,k), T given by A026780.

A026791.name: Triangle in which n-th row lists juxtaposed lexicographically ordered partitions of n; e.g., the partitions of 3 (1+1+1,1+2,3) appear as 1,1,1,1,2,3 in row 3.

A026792.name: List of juxtaposed reverse-lexicographically ordered partitions of the positive integers.

A026793.name: Juxtaposed partitions of 1,2,3,... into distinct parts, ordered by number of terms and then lexicographically.

A026794.name: Triangular array T read by rows: T(n,k) = number of partitions of n in which least part is k, 1<=k<=n.
formula: T(n, k) = sum{T(n-k, i), k<=i<=n-k} for k=1, 2, ..., m, T(n, k)=0 for k=m+1, ..., n-1, where m=floor(n/2); T(n, n)=1 for n >= 1.
G.f.: G(t,x)=sum(t^i*x^i/product(1-x^j, j=i..infinity), i=1..infinity). - _Emeric Deutsch_, Feb 19 2006
T(n,k) = T(n-1,k-1) - T(n-k,k-1) for n>=2 and 2<=k<=(n-1) with T(n,1) = A000041(n-1), T(n,n) = 1 for n>=1 and T(n,k) = 0 for k>n. - _Johannes W. Meijer_, Jun 21 2010
T(k,k) = 1 and T(n,1) = row sum (n-1); thus Meijer's 2010 formula generates the triangle without a priori reference to A000041 (the partition sequence). - _Bob Selcoe_, Sep 03 2016

A026796.name: Number of partitions of n in which the least part is 3.
formula: a(n) = p(n-3) - p(n-4) - p(n-5) + p(n-6), where p(n) = A000041(n). - _Bob Selcoe_, Aug 07 2014
G.f.: Sum_{k>=1} x^(3*k) / Product_{j=1..k-1} (1 - x^j). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Nov 25 2020

A026797.name: Number of partitions of n in which the least part is 4.
formula: G.f.: Sum_{k>=1} x^(4*k) / Product_{j=1..k-1} (1 - x^j). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Nov 25 2020

A026798.name: Number of partitions of n in which the least part is 5.
formula: a(n+5) is given by p(n) - p(n-1) - p(n-2) + 2p(n-5) - p(n-8) - p(n-9) + p(n-10) where p(n) = A000041(n). - _Shanzhen Gao_, Oct 28 2010 [sign of 10 and offset of formula corrected by _Jason Kimberley_, Nov 11 2011]

A026799.name: Number of partitions of n in which the least part is 6.
formula: G.f.: Sum_{k>=1} x^(6*k) / Product_{j=1..k-1} (1 - x^j). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Nov 25 2020

A026800.name: Number of partitions of n in which the least part is 7.
formula: a(n) = p(n-7) -p(n-8) -p(n-9) +p(n-12) +2*p(n-14) -p(n-16) -p(n-17) -p(n-18) -p(n-19) +2*p(n-21) +p(n-23) -p(n-26) -p(n-27) +p(n-28) where p(n)=A000041(n) including the implicit p(n)=0 for negative n. - _Shanzhen Gao_, Oct 28 2010; offset corrected / made explicit by _Jason Kimberley_, Feb 03 2011
G.f.: Sum_{k>=1} x^(7*k) / Product_{j=1..k-1} (1 - x^j). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Nov 25 2020

A026801.name: Number of partitions of n in which the least part is 8.
formula: G.f.: Sum_{k>=1} x^(8*k) / Product_{j=1..k-1} (1 - x^j). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Nov 25 2020

A026802.name: Number of partitions of n in which the least part is 9.
formula: G.f.: Sum_{k>=1} x^(9*k) / Product_{j=1..k-1} (1 - x^j). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Nov 25 2020

A026803.name: Number of partitions of n in which the least part is 10.
formula: G.f.: Sum_{k>=1} x^(10*k) / Product_{j=1..k-1} (1 - x^j). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Nov 25 2020

A026804.name: Number of partitions of n in which the least part is odd.
formula: a(n) ~ exp(Pi*sqrt(2*n/3)) / (4*sqrt(3)*n) * (1 - (sqrt(3/2)/Pi + 25*Pi/(24*sqrt(6))) / sqrt(n) + (25/16 + 2929*Pi^2/6912)/n). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Jul 06 2019, extended Nov 02 2019

A026805.name: Number of partitions of n in which the least part is even.
formula: a(n) ~ Pi * exp(Pi*sqrt(2*n/3)) / (3 * 2^(5/2) * n^(3/2)) * (1 - (3*sqrt(3/2)/Pi + 61*Pi/(24*sqrt(6))) / sqrt(n)). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Jul 06 2019, extended Nov 02 2019

A026806.name: a(n) = number of numbers k such that only one partition of n has least part k.

A026807.name: Triangular array T read by rows: T(n,k) = number of partitions of n in which every part is >=k, for k=1,2,...,n.
formula: T(n, k) = T(n, k+1) + T(n-k, k), T(n, k) = 1 if n/2 < k <= n. - _Franklin T. Adams-Watters_, Jan 24 2005; _Tilman Piesk_, Feb 20 2016
T(n, k) = A000041(n..n-t) * transpose(A231599(k-1, 0..t)) with t = A000217(k-1). - _Tilman Piesk_, Feb 20 2016
Equals A026794 * A000012 as infinite lower triangular matrices. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Jan 31 2008

A026808.name: a(n) is the number of products P of distinct positive integers satisfying P <= n.

A026810.name: Number of partitions of n in which the greatest part is 4.
formula: a(n) = round( (n^3 + 3*n^2 -9*n*(n mod 2))/144 ). _Washington Bomfim_, Jan 06 2021 and Jul 03 2012
a(2n) = a(2n-1) + a(n+2) - a(n-2). - _Gregory L. Simay_, Jul 28 2019

A026811.name: Number of partitions of n in which the greatest part is 5.

A026812.name: Number of partitions of n in which the greatest part is 6.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{m=1..floor(n/6)} Sum_{l=m..floor((n-m)/5)} Sum_{k=l..floor((n-l-m)/4)} Sum_{j=k..floor((n-k-l-m)/3)} Sum_{i=j..floor((n-j-k-l-m)/2)} 1. - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Jun 29 2019

A026813.name: Number of partitions of n in which the greatest part is 7.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{o=1..floor(n/7)} Sum_{m=o..floor((n-o)/6)} Sum_{l=m..floor((n-m-o)/5)} Sum_{k=l..floor((n-l-m-o)/4)} Sum_{j=k..floor((n-k-l-m-o)/3} Sum_{i=j..floor((n-j-k-l-m-o)/2)} 1. - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Jun 30 2019

A026814.name: Number of partitions of n in which the greatest part is 8.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{p=1..floor(n/8)} Sum_{o=p..floor((n-p)/7)} Sum_{m=o..floor((n-o-p)/6)} Sum_{l=m..floor((n-m-o-p)/5)} Sum_{k=l..floor((n-l-m-o-p)/4)} Sum_{j=k..floor((n-k-l-m-o-p)/3)} Sum_{i=j..floor((n-j-k-l-m-o-p)/2)} 1. - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Jul 04 2019

A026815.name: Number of partitions of n in which the greatest part is 9.

A026816.name: Number of partitions of n in which the greatest part is 10.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{r=1..floor(n/10)} Sum_{q=r..floor((n-r)/9)} Sum_{p=q..floor((n-q-r)/8)} Sum_{o=p..floor((n-p-q-r)/7)} Sum_{m=o..floor((n-o-p-q-r)/6)} Sum_{l=m..floor((n-m-o-p-q-r)/5)} Sum_{k=l..floor((n-l-m-o-p-q-r)/4)} Sum_{j=k..floor((n-k-l-m-o-p-q-r)/3)} Sum_{i=j..floor((n-j-k-l-m-o-p-q-r)/2)} 1. - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Jul 13 2019

A026817.name: Number of sets which can be obtained by selecting unique elements from two sets with 2n and 3n elements respectively and n common elements.

A026818.name: Largest digit of n concatenated with smallest digit of n is prime.

A026819.name: a(n) = least k such that if 1<=h<=n then T(n,k)>=T(n,h), T given by A008284.

A026820.name: Euler's table: triangular array T read by rows, where T(n,k) = number of partitions in which every part is <= k for 1 <= k <= n. Also number of partitions of n into at most k parts.
formula: T(n,k) = T(n,k-1) + T(n-k,k). - _Thomas Dybdahl Ahle_, Jun 13 2011
T(n,k) = Sum_{i=1..min(k,floor(n/2))} T(n-i,i) + Sum_{j=1+floor(n/2)..k} A000041(n-j). - _Bob Selcoe_, Aug 22 2014 [corrected by _Álvar Ibeas_, Mar 15 2018]

A026821.name: Triangular array T read by rows: T(n,k) = number of partitions of n into distinct parts, the least being k, for k=1,2,...,n.
formula: T(n, k) = T(n-k, k+1) + ... + T(n-k, n-k) for 1<=k<=m and T(n, k)=0 for m+1<=k<=n-1, where m=[ (n-1)/2 ]; T(n, n)=1 for n >= 1.

A026824.name: Number of partitions of n into distinct parts, the least being 3.

A026825.name: Number of partitions of n into distinct parts, the least being 4.
formula: G.f.: Sum_{k>=1} x^(k*(k + 7)/2) / Product_{j=1..k-1} (1 - x^j). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Nov 24 2020

A026826.name: Number of partitions of n into distinct parts, the least being 5.
formula: G.f.: Sum_{k>=1} x^(k*(k + 9)/2) / Product_{j=1..k-1} (1 - x^j). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Nov 24 2020

A026827.name: Number of partitions of n into distinct parts, the least being 6.
formula: G.f.: Sum_{k>=1} x^(k*(k + 11)/2) / Product_{j=1..k-1} (1 - x^j). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Nov 24 2020

A026828.name: Number of partitions of n into distinct parts, the least being 7.
formula: G.f.: Sum_{k>=1} x^(k*(k + 13)/2) / Product_{j=1..k-1} (1 - x^j). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Nov 24 2020

A026829.name: Number of partitions of n into distinct parts, the least being 8.
formula: G.f.: Sum_{k>=1} x^(k*(k + 15)/2) / Product_{j=1..k-1} (1 - x^j). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Nov 24 2020

A026830.name: Number of partitions of n into distinct parts, the least being 9.
formula: G.f.: Sum_{k>=1} x^(k*(k + 17)/2) / Product_{j=1..k-1} (1 - x^j). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Nov 25 2020

A026831.name: Number of partitions of n into distinct parts, the least being 10.
formula: G.f.: Sum_{k>=1} x^(k*(k + 19)/2) / Product_{j=1..k-1} (1 - x^j). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Nov 25 2020

A026832.name: Number of partitions of n into distinct parts, the least being odd.
formula: G.f.: Sum_{ k >= 1 } x^(k*(k+1)/2)/((1+x^k)*Product_{i=1..k} (1-x^i) ). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Aug 10 2004
G.f.: Sum_{k>=1} x^(2k-1)*Product_{j>=2k} (1 + x^j). - _Emeric Deutsch_, Mar 29 2006

A026833.name: Number of partitions of n into distinct parts, the least being even.

A026834.name: a(n) = number of numbers k such that only one partition of n into distinct parts has least part k.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} [A026821(n, k) == 1]. - _Sean A. Irvine_, Oct 14 2019

A026835.name: Triangular array read by rows: T(n,k) = number of partitions of n into distinct parts in which every part is >=k, for k=1,2,...,n.
formula: T(n, k) = 1 + Sum(T(i, j): i>=j>k and i+j=n+1). - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Jan 01 2003
T(n, k) > 1 iff 2*k < n. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Jan 01 2003

A026836.name: Triangular array T read by rows: T(n,k) = number of partitions of n into distinct parts, the greatest being k, for k=1,2,...,n.
formula: T(n, k) = coefficient of x^n in x^k*Product_{i=1..k-1} (1+x^i). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Aug 07 2003

A026837.name: Number of partitions of n into distinct parts, the greatest being odd.
formula: G.f.: sum(k>=1, x^(2k-1) * prod(j=1..2k-2, 1+x^j ) ). - _Emeric Deutsch_, Apr 04 2006

A026838.name: Number of partitions of n into distinct parts, the greatest being even.
formula: G.f.: sum(k>=1, x^(2k) * prod(j=1..2k-1, 1+x^j ) ). - _Emeric Deutsch_, Apr 04 2006

A026839.name: a(n) = MAX{T(n,k} for k=1,2,...,n, T given in A026836.

A026840.name: Triangular array T read by rows: T(n,k) = number of partitions of n into distinct parts <= k, for k=1,2,...n.

A026841.name: a(n) = T(2n,n-4), T given by A026725.
formula: G.f.: (x^4*C(x)^10)/(1-x*C(x)^3) where C(x) is the g.f. of A000108. - _Philippe Deléham_, Feb 02 2014

A026842.name: a(n) = T(2n,n-3), T given by A026725.
formula: G.f.: (x^3*C(x)^8)/(1-x*C(x)^3) where C(x) is the g.f. of A000108. - _Philippe Deléham_, Feb 02 2014

A026843.name: a(n) = T(2n,n+3), T given by A026725.
formula: G.f.: (x^3*C(x)^7)/(1-x*C(x)^3) where C(x) is the g.f. of A000108. - _Philippe Deléham_, Feb 02 2014
a(n) ~ phi^(3*n-4) / sqrt(5), where phi = A001622 = (1+sqrt(5))/2 is the golden ratio. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Jul 19 2019

A026844.name: a(n) = T(2n,n+4), T given by A026725.
formula: G.f.: (x^4*C(x)^9)/(1-x*C(x)^3) where C(x) is the g.f. of A000108. - _Philippe Deléham_, Feb 02 2014
a(n) ~ phi^(3*n-5) / sqrt(5), where phi = A001622 = (1+sqrt(5))/2 is the golden ratio. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Jul 19 2019

A026845.name: Sum_{mu a partition of n} (f^mu/n!)^{-2} where f^mu is the number of standard Young tableaux of shape mu.

A026846.name: a(n) = T(2n+1,n+4), T given by A026725.
formula: G.f.: (x^3*C(x)^8)/(1-x*C(x)^3) where C(x) is the g.f. of A000108. - _Philippe Deléham_, Feb 02 2014

A026847.name: a(n) = T(n,m) + T(n,m+1) + ... + T(n,n), where m=[ (n+1)/2 ], T given by A026725.

A026848.name: a(n) = T(2n,n-4), T given by A026736.
formula: G.f.: (x^4*C(x)^10)/(1-x*C(x)^3) where C(x) is the g.f. of A000108. - _Philippe Deléham_, Feb 02 2014

A026849.name: a(n) = T(2n,n-3), T given by A026736.
formula: G.f.: (x^3*C(x)^8)/(1-x*C(x)^3) where C(x) is the g.f. of A000108. - _Philippe Deléham_, Feb 02 2014

A026850.name: a(n) = T(2n,n+1), T given by A026736.
formula: G.f.: (x * C(x)^3)/(1 - x/sqrt(1 - 4 * x)) where C(x) is the g.f. for Catalan numbers A000108. - _David Callan_, Jan 16 2016

A026851.name: a(n) = T(2n,n+2), T given by A026736.
formula: G.f.: (x * C(x)^5)/(1 - x/sqrt(1 - 4 * x)) where C(x) is the g.f. for Catalan numbers A000108. - _David Callan_, Jan 16 2016

A026852.name: a(n) = T(2n,n+3), T given by A026736.

A026853.name: a(n) = T(2n,n+4), T given by A026736.
formula: G.f.: x^4*C(x)^9/(1 -x/sqrt(1-4*x)), where C(x) if the g.f. for Catalan numbers A000108. - _G. C. Greubel_, Jul 17 2019

A026854.name: a(n) = T(2n+1,n+1), T given by A026736.
formula: G.f.: C(x)^2/(1 - x/sqrt(1-4*x)) where C(x) = g.f. for Catalan numbers A000108. - _David Callan_, Jan 16 2016

A026855.name: a(n) = T(2n+1,n+2), T given by A026736.
formula: G.f.: (x*C(x)^4)/(1 - x/sqrt(1 - 4*x)) where C(x) is the g.f. for Catalan numbers A000108. - _David Callan_, Jan 16 2016

A026856.name: a(n) = T(2n+1,n+3), T given by A026736.
formula: G.f.: (x^2 * C(x)^6)/(1 - x/sqrt(1-4*x)) where C(x) = g.f. for Catalan numbers A000108. - _David Callan_, Jan 16 2016

A026857.name: a(n) = T(2n+1,n+4), T given by A026736.
formula: a(n) ~ phi^(3*n-4) / sqrt(5), where phi = A001622 = (1+sqrt(5))/2 is the golden ratio. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Jul 19 2019

A026858.name: Number of letters in n (in Italian).

A026865.name: Number of labeled chain graphs.
formula: a(n) = -Sum_{k=1..n} binomial(n, k) * b(k) * a(n - k) * 2^(k*(n-k)) with a(0) = b(0) = 1 and b(n) = -Sum_{k=0..n-1} binomial(n, k) * b(k) * 2^(binomial(n-r, 2)) [from Steinsky]. - _Sean A. Irvine_, Oct 15 2019

A026876.name: T(2n+1, n+1), T given by A026758.

A026878.name: a(n) = T(2n+1,n+3), T given by A026758.

A026898.name: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} (n-k+1)^k.
formula: G.f.: Sum_{n>=0} x^n/(1 - (n+1)*x). - _Paul D. Hanna_, Sep 13 2011
G.f.: G(0) where G(k) = 1 + x*(2*k*x-1)/((2*k*x+x-1) - x*(2*k*x+x-1)^2/(x*(2*k*x+x-1) + (2*k*x+2*x-1)/G(k+1) )); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jan 26 2013
E.g.f.: Sum_{n>=0} Integral^n exp((n+1)*x) dx^n, where Integral^n F(x) dx^n is the n-th integration of F(x) with no constant of integration. - _Paul D. Hanna_, Dec 28 2013
O.g.f.: Sum_{n>=0} n! * x^n/(1-x)^(n+1) / Product_{k=1..n} (1 + k*x). - _Paul D. Hanna_, Jul 20 2014
log(a(n)) ~ (1 - 1/LambertW(exp(1)*n)) * n * log(1 + n/LambertW(exp(1)*n)). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Jun 15 2021

A026905.name: Partial sums of the partition numbers A000041.
formula: G.f.: -1/(1 - x) + (1/(1 - x))*Product_{k>=1} 1/(1 - x^k). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Dec 25 2016

A026906.name: Number of sums S of distinct positive integers satisfying S <= n.
formula: G.f.: -1/(1 - x) + (1/(1 - x))*Product_{k>=1} (1 + x^k). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Dec 25 2016

A026907.name: Triangular array T read by rows (9-diamondization of Pascal's triangle). Step 1: t(n,k) = sum of 9 entries in diamond-shaped subarray of Pascal's triangle having vertices C(n,k), C(n+4,k+2), C(n+2,k), C(n+2,k+2). Step 2: T(n,k) = t(n,k) - t(0,0) + 1.

A026908.name: T(2n,n), T given by A026907.
formula: a(n) = 4^n*GAMMA(n+1/2)*(38+99*n+49*n^2)*Pi^(-1/2)/GAMMA(n+3)-18 (based on guessed recurrence) - _Mark van Hoeij_, Oct 30 2011

A026944.name: E.g.f. is inverse function to y -> integral from 0 to y of exp(-s^2).
formula: Nonzero constant terms of the polynomials in t defined by P_1=1, P_{n+1}=P'n+2*n*t*P_n; E.g.f. = (1/2*sqrt(Pi)*erf)^{-1}(x)
E.g.f. A(x) satisfies the differential equation A'(x)=exp(A(x)^2) [From _Vladimir Kruchinin_, Jan 22 2011]
Let D denote the operator g(x) -> d/dx(exp(x^2)*g(x)). Then a(n) = D^(2*n-2)(1) evaluated at x = 0. See [Dominici, Example 11]. - Peter Bala, Sep 08 2011
